This is an Akubra adapter for the DuraCloud REST api.

Build Instructions
==================
1) Install DuraCloud dependencies in local repository

mvn install:install-file -DgroupId=org.duracloud -DartifactId=common -Dversion=1.0.0 -Dpackaging=jar -Dfile=resources/lib/common-1.0.0.jar
mvn install:install-file -DgroupId=org.duracloud -DartifactId=storageprovider -Dversion=1.0.0 -Dpackaging=jar -Dfile=resources/lib/storageprovider-1.0.0.jar
mvn install:install-file -DgroupId=org.duracloud -DartifactId=storeclient -Dversion=1.0.0 -Dpackaging=jar -Dfile=resources/lib/storeclient-1.0.0.jar -DpomFile=resources/lib/storeclient-1.0.0.pom

2) Compile and install

mvn install

Starting/Stopping a DuraCloud Instance
======================================
To start:
  [Launch a DuraCloud instance]
    Login to the AWS Management Console: https://console.aws.amazon.com/
    Launch a small-CPU instance of the private AMI: ami-3333d05a
    Choose the "default" security group (allows connections to port 8080)
    Use your own keypair (allows you to ssh in if you want to look at logs, etc)
  [Wait for it to start]
    After the EC2 instance starts, the DuraCloud service will automatically
    deploy. This will take a few minutes to complete. When ready, the following
    URL: http://host:8080/durastore/stores ..should result in a simple HTML
    page saying that "The Storage Provider Utility must be initialized (..etc)".
  [POST the initialization xml file to this URL (e.g, using Poster for Firefox)]
    This file provides the necessary info for DuraCloud to connect to the
    backend storage provider (e.g. an S3 account).
    When finished, you should get a 200 text/plain response saying
    "Initialization Successful".  Now when you GET this URL, you should see
    the information for the store you just initialized with.

To stop:
  Use the AWS Management Console to terminate the instance.